    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the students. I also want to address the pushback from some legal scholars who argue this is basically just \"judicial activism.\" Could you add a section that briefly mentions why some people think this concept is problematic or oversteps what the Constitution actually says?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process, while championing civil liberties, has been criticized by some legal scholars as \"judicial activism,\" where judges are seen as overstepping their bounds and creating new rights not explicitly stated in the Constitution. Critics argue that this approach undermines the principle of separation of powers, allowing unelected judges to make law rather than interpreting it. They believe that such decisions should be left to the legislative process, where elected representatives debate and decide on the boundaries of rights. This perspective contends that substantive due process can lead to unpredictable and inconsistent rulings, as judges' personal beliefs and values may influence their interpretation of what constitutes a \"fundamental right.\" Ultimately, this debate highlights the tension between a living Constitution that adapts to societal changes and a more originalist view that adheres strictly to the text and historical context of the Constitution.",
      "source": "target",
